com.ibm.team.process.common

Interface IIteration

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IAuditable, IAuditableHandle, IItem, IItemHandle, IIterationHandle, IManagedItem, IManagedItemHandle, INamed, IProcessItem, IProcessItemHandle

    public interface IIteration
extends IIterationHandle, IProcessItem
    An iteration in a project area. Each of the development lines in a project area can contain an arbitrary hierarchy of iterations.
    Since:
    0.6

    • Method Detail

      • getId

        java.lang.String getId()
        Returns the id of this iteration or null if no id has been set.

        In order for this item to be saved to the repository this field must have a non-null value, so it is safe to assume that this method will not return null if it is an immutable copy fetched from the repository. It is possible for an incomplete/invalid working copy, however, to return null.

        Returns:
        the id of this iteration or null

      • setId

        void setId(java.lang.String identifier)
        Sets the id of this iteration. The provided identifier may not be null.
        Parameters:
        identifier - the new identifier, may not be null

      • getLabel

        java.lang.String getLabel()
        This convenience method returns the name of this iteration if the name is not null and is not a whitespace string. Otherwise it returns this iteration's id, which may be null if this item is a working copy (@see getId().
        Returns:
        the name or id of this iteration or null

      • getChildren

        IIterationHandle[] getChildren()
        Returns the iterations into which this iteration is divided. Returns an empty array if this iteration is undivided.
        Returns:
        the child iterations or an empty array

      • setChildren

        void setChildren(IIterationHandle[] children)
        Sets the child iterations of this iteration.

        Note that in order to save the iteration, the child iterations will also have to declare this iteration as their parent. When establishing a new parent/child relationship, the parent/child iterations have to be saved together.

        Parameters:
        children - the child iterations

      • insertChildAfter

        void insertChildAfter(IIterationHandle child,
                    IIterationHandle anchor)
        Inserts the iteration identified by the given handle into the list of child iterations right after the given anchor. In order to complete the bi-directional relationship, callers must also set this iteration as parent of the new child. If the given iteration is already a child of this iteration, this method does not have any effect. If the anchor is null the element is added at the beginning of the list.
        Parameters:
        child - a handle for the new child
        anchor - the current child after which the new child should be added or null

      • addChild

        void addChild(IIterationHandle child)
        Adds the iteration identified by the given handle at the end of the list of child iterations.

        Note that in order to save the iteration, the child iteration will also have to declare this iteration as its parent. When establishing a new parent/child relationship, the parent/child iterations have to be saved together.

        Parameters:
        child - a handle for the new child

      • removeChild

        void removeChild(IIterationHandle child)
        Removes the iteration identified by the given handle from the list of child iterations. If the iteration is not a child of this iteration, this method does not have any effect. In order to ensure the consistency of the bi-directional relationship, the caller has also to remove the this iteration as parent from the given iteration.
        Parameters:
        child - a handle to the existing child

      • getParent

        IIterationHandle getParent()
        Returns the parent iteration of this iteration or null if this iteration does not have a parent. Iterations which do not have a parent are either root iterations (@see setDevelopmentLine(IDevelopmentLineHandle)) or they are misconfigured children (@see #setChildren()).
        Returns:
        the parent iteration or null

      • setParent

        void setParent(IIterationHandle parent)
        Set the parent iteration of this iteration. This will be null to indicate that the iteration is a root iteration.

        Note that in order to save the iteration, the parent iteration will also have to contain this iteration as a child. If the parent is null, the development line will have to specify that it contains this root iteration. When establishing a new parent/child relationship, the parent/child iterations have to be saved together.

        Parameters:
        the - parent iteration

      • getDevelopmentLine

        IDevelopmentLineHandle getDevelopmentLine()
        Returns the development line to which this iteration belongs or null if no development line has been set.

        In order for this item to be saved to the repository this field must have a non-null value, so it is safe to assume that this method will not return null if it is an immutable copy fetched from the repository. It is possible for an incomplete/invalid working copy, however, to return null.

        Returns:
        the development line to which this iteration belongs or null

      • setDevelopmentLine

        void setDevelopmentLine(IDevelopmentLineHandle developmentLine)
        Returns the development line to which this iteration belongs.

        Note that in order to save the iteration, the development line will also have to contain this iteration (either directly or transitively). When adding a new iteration to a development line, the line, iteration, and any parent/child iterations have to be saved together.

        Parameters:
        the - development line

      • isArchived

        boolean isArchived()
        Returns whether or not this iteration is archived.

        In order to archive an iteration, use the process client library or process server service.

        Returns:
        whether or not this iteration is archived

      • getStartDate

        java.util.Date getStartDate()
        Returns this iteration's start date or null if no start date has been configured.
        Returns:
        the iteration's start date or null

      • setStartDate

        void setStartDate(java.util.Date date)
        Sets this iteration's start date. If this iteration has an end date set, the given date must be non-null and must come before the end date.
        Parameters:
        date - the start date or null

      • getEndDate

        java.util.Date getEndDate()
        Returns this iteration's end date or null if no end date has been configured.
        Returns:
        the iteration's end date or null

      • setEndDate

        void setEndDate(java.util.Date date)
        Sets this iteration's end date. If specifying a non-null end date, this iteration must have a start date set which comes before the end date.
        Parameters:
        date - the end date or null

      • hasDeliverable

        Parameters:
        hasDeliverable - whether or not this iteration has a deliverable
